[src:containers-vs-vms/application-virtualization] In this context, the term "virtualization" refers to the artifact being encapsulated (application), which is quite different from its meaning in hardware virtualization, where it refers to the artifact being abstracted (physical hardware).
[src:containers-vs-vms/application-virtualization] Full application virtualization requires a virtualization layer.
[src:containers-vs-vms/application-virtualization] Application virtualization layers replace part of the runtime environment normally provided by the operating system.
[src:containers-vs-vms/application-virtualization] The layer intercepts all disk operations of virtualized applications and transparently redirects them to a virtualized location, often a single file.
[src:containers-vs-vms/application-virtualization] The application remains unaware that it accesses a virtual resource instead of a physical one.
[src:containers-vs-vms/application-virtualization] Since the application is now working with one file instead of many files spread throughout the system, it becomes easy to run the application on a different computer, and previously incompatible applications can be run side-by-side.
[src:containers-vs-vms/application-virtualization] Application virtualization allows applications to run in environments that do not suit the native application.
[src:containers-vs-vms/application-virtualization] For example, Wine allows some Microsoft Windows applications to run on Linux.
[src:containers-vs-vms/application-virtualization] Application virtualization reduces system integration and administration costs by maintaining a common software baseline across multiple diverse computers in an organization.
[src:containers-vs-vms/application-virtualization] Lesser integration protects the operating system and other applications from poorly-written or buggy code.
[src:containers-vs-vms/application-virtualization] In some cases, it provides memory protection and IDE-style debugging features, and may even run applications that are not written correctly, such as applications that try to store user data in a read-only system-owned location.
[src:containers-vs-vms/application-virtualization] Isolating applications from the operating system has security benefits as well, as the exposure of the virtualized application does not automatically entail the exposure of the entire OS.
[src:containers-vs-vms/application-virtualization] Application virtualization also enables simplified operating system migrations.
[src:containers-vs-vms/application-virtualization] Applications can be transferred to removable media or between computers without the need of installing them, becoming portable software.
[src:containers-vs-vms/application-virtualization] Application virtualization uses fewer resources than a separate virtual machine.
[src:containers-vs-vms/application-virtualization] Not all computer programs can be virtualized.
[src:containers-vs-vms/application-virtualization] Some examples include applications that require a device driver (a form of integration with the OS) and 16-bit applications that need to run in shared memory space.
[src:containers-vs-vms/application-virtualization] Anti-virus programs and applications that require heavy OS integration, such as WindowBlinds or StyleXP are difficult to virtualize.
[src:containers-vs-vms/application-virtualization] Moreover, in software licensing, application virtualization bears great licensing pitfalls, mainly because both the application-virtualization software and the virtualized applications must be correctly licensed.
[src:containers-vs-vms/application-virtualization] For this reason, specialist application compatibility fixes (shims) may still be needed, even if the application is virtualized.
[src:containers-vs-vms/application-virtualization] Functional discrepancies within the multicompatibility model are an additional limitation, where utility-driven access points are shared within a public network.
[src:containers-vs-vms/application-virtualization] These limitations are overcome by designating a system-level share point driver.
[src:containers-vs-vms/full-virtualization] In computing, **virtualization** (or **virtualisation** in Commonwealth English; see spelling differences,) abbreviated as **v12n**, is a series of technologies that allows dividing of physical computing resources into a series of virtual machines, operating systems, processes or containers.
[src:containers-vs-vms/full-virtualization] Virtualization began in the 1960s with IBM CP/CMS.
[src:containers-vs-vms/full-virtualization] The control program CP provided each user with a simulated stand-alone System/360 computer.
[src:containers-vs-vms/full-virtualization] In hardware virtualization, the *host machine* is the machine that is used by the virtualization and the *guest machine* is the virtual machine.
[src:containers-vs-vms/full-virtualization] The words *host* and *guest* are used to distinguish the software that runs on the physical machine from the software that runs on the virtual machine.
[src:containers-vs-vms/full-virtualization] The software or firmware that creates a virtual machine on the host hardware is called a *hypervisor* or *virtual machine monitor*.
[src:containers-vs-vms/full-virtualization] Hardware virtualization is not the same as hardware emulation.
[src:containers-vs-vms/full-virtualization] Hardware-assisted virtualization facilitates building a virtual machine monitor and allows guest OSes to be run in isolation.
[src:containers-vs-vms/full-virtualization] Desktop virtualization is the concept of separating the logical desktop from the physical machine.
[src:containers-vs-vms/full-virtualization] Operating system-level virtualization, also known as containerization, refers to an operating system feature in which the kernel allows the existence of multiple isolated user-space instances.
[src:containers-vs-vms/full-virtualization] The usual goal of virtualization is to centralize administrative tasks while improving scalability and overall hardware-resource utilization.
[src:containers-vs-vms/full-virtualization] A form of virtualization was first demonstrated with IBM's CP-40 research system in 1967, then distributed via open source in CP/CMS in 1967–1972, and re-implemented in IBM's VM family from 1972 to the present.
[src:containers-vs-vms/full-virtualization] Each CP/CMS user was provided a simulated, stand-alone computer.
[src:containers-vs-vms/full-virtualization] Each such virtual machine had the complete capabilities of the underlying machine, and (for its user) the virtual machine was indistinguishable from a private system.
